[Student "S"]
{East is to play 3NT. South leads the \HK. North plays the \H6.

Winners:   \S=3  \H=1  \D=1  \C=3  Total = 8

You just need one more winner and it could come from the \D suit if it happens to split 3-3. But you have another possibility. Suppose you let South hold the first trick and he decides to play another \H? You would have two \H winners.

This isn't a true hold-up play although it does look like one. This play has the rather fancy name of Bath Coup, (named from Bath, England). Presumably South has led from \H K Q 10 9 5 and North has played his singleton \H6. If South realizes that North has played his lowest card he will take that as a discouraging signal and will play a different suit. So you throw out your \H7 rather than the \H3. Now South may think that North is encouraging him to continue, just what you want.

Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.

I sure hope that when you play this hand South falls for your Bath Coup.

Because if he doesn't you're going to have to end-play him.

Do you see how that might happen?}
[Play "W"]HK

